  abstract = {Studies of exoplanet demographics require large samples and precise constraints on exoplanet host stars. Using the homogeneous Kepler stellar properties derived using Gaia Data Release 2 by Berger et al. (2020), we re-compute Kepler planet radii and incident fluxes and investigate their distributions with stellar mass and age. We measure the stellar mass dependence of the planet radius valley to be \$d \textbackslash backslashlog R\_\{\textbackslash backslashmathrm\{p\}\}\$/\$d \textbackslash backslashlog M\_\textbackslash backslashstar = 0.26\^\{+0.21\}\_\{-0.16\}\$, consistent with the slope predicted by a planet mass dependence on stellar mass (\$0.24-0.35\$) and core-powered mass-loss (0.33). We also find first evidence of a stellar age dependence of the planet populations straddling the radius valley. Specifically, we determine that the fraction of super-Earths (\$1-1.8 \textbackslash backslashmathrm\{R\_\textbackslash backslashoplus\}\$) to sub-Neptunes (\$1.8-3.5 \textbackslash backslashmathrm\{R\_\textbackslash backslashoplus\}\$) increases from \$0.61 \textbackslash backslashpm 0.09\$ at young ages (\textbackslash textless 1 Gyr) to \$1.00 \textbackslash backslashpm 0.10\$ at old ages (\textbackslash textgreater 1 Gyr), consistent with the prediction by core-powered mass-loss that the mechanism shaping the radius valley operates over Gyr timescales. Additionally, we find a tentative decrease in the radii of relatively cool (\$F\_\{\textbackslash backslashmathrm\{p\}\} \textbackslash textless 150 \textbackslash backslashmathrm\{F\_\textbackslash backslashoplus\}\$) sub-Neptunes over Gyr timescales, which suggests that these planets may possess H/He envelopes instead of higher mean molecular weight atmospheres. We confirm the existence of planets within the hot sub-Neptunian "desert" (\$2.2 \textbackslash textless R\_\{\textbackslash backslashmathrm\{p\}\} \textbackslash textless 3.8 \textbackslash backslashmathrm\{R\_\textbackslash backslashoplus\}\$, \$F\_\{\textbackslash backslashmathrm\{p\}\} \textbackslash textgreater 650 \textbackslash backslashmathrm\{F\_\textbackslash backslashoplus\}\$) and show that these planets are preferentially orbiting more evolved stars compared to other planets at similar incident fluxes. In addition, we identify candidates for cool (\$F\_\{\textbackslash backslashmathrm\{p\}\} \textbackslash textless 20 \textbackslash backslashmathrm\{F\_\textbackslash backslashoplus\}\$) inflated Jupiters, present a revised list of habitable zone candidates, and find that the ages of single- and multiple-transiting planet systems are statistically indistinguishable.},
