  abstract = {We present a comprehensive catalog of cool (period P \& 2 yr) transiting planet candidates in the four-year light curves from the prime Kepler mission. Most of the candidates show only one or two transits and have largely been missed in the original Kepler Object of Interest catalog. Our catalog is based on all known such candidates in the literature as well as new candidates from the search in this paper, and provides a resource to explore the planet population near the snow line of Sun-like stars. We homogeneously performed pixel-level vetting, stellar characterization with Gaia parallax and archival/Subaru spectroscopy, and light-curve modeling to derive planet parameters and to eliminate stellar binaries. The resulting clean sample consists of 67 planet candidates whose radii are typically constrained to 5\%, in which 23 are newly reported. The number of Jupiter-sized candidates (29 with r \textbackslash textgreater 8 R{$\bigoplus$}) in the sample is consistent with the Doppler occurrence. The smaller candidates are more prevalent (23 with 4 \textbackslash textless r/R{$\bigoplus$} \textbackslash textless 8, 15 with r/R{$\bigoplus$} \textbackslash textless 4) and suggest that long-period Neptune-sized planets are at least as common as the Jupiter-sized ones, although our sample is yet to be corrected for detection completeness. If the sample is assumed to be complete, these numbers imply the occurrence rate of 0.39 {$\pm$} 0.07 planets with 4 \textbackslash textless r/R{$\bigoplus$} \textbackslash textless 14 and 2 \textbackslash textless P/yr \textbackslash textless 20 per FGK dwarf. The stars hosting candidates with r \textbackslash textgreater 4 R{$\bigoplus$} have systematically higher [Fe/H] than the Kepler field stars, providing evidence that giant planet\textendash metallicity correlation extends to P \textbackslash textgreater 2 yr.},
