  abstract = {Several models have been introduced in order to explain the radius distribution in exoplanet radii observed by Fulton et al. (2017) with one peak at \$\textbackslash backslashrm \textbackslash backslashsim 1.3 R\_\{\textbackslash backslashoplus\} \$ the other at \$\textbackslash backslashrm \textbackslash backslashsim 2.4 R\_\{\textbackslash backslashoplus\} \$ and the minimum at \$\textbackslash backslashrm \textbackslash backslashsim 1.75R\_\{\textbackslash backslashoplus\} \$. In this paper we focus on the hypothesis that the exoplanet size distribution is caused by stellar XUV-induced atmospheric loss. We evolve \$10\^\{6\}\$ synthetic exoplanets by exposing them to XUV irradiation from synthetic ZAMS stars. For each planet we set a different interior composition which ranged from \$\textbackslash backslashrm 100 \textbackslash backslash: wt\textbackslash backslash\%\$ Fe (very dense) through \$\textbackslash backslashrm 100 \textbackslash backslash: wt\textbackslash backslash\%\$ \$\textbackslash backslashrm MgSiO\_\{3\}\$ (average density) and to \$\textbackslash backslashrm 100 \textbackslash backslash: wt\textbackslash backslash\%\$ \$\textbackslash backslashrm H\_\{2\}O\$ ice (low density) with varying hydrogen envelop sizes which varied from \$\textbackslash backslashrm 0 \textbackslash backslash: wt\textbackslash backslash\%\$ (a negligible envelop) to \$\textbackslash backslashrm 100 \textbackslash backslash: wt\textbackslash backslash\%\$ (a negligible core). Our simulations were able to replicate the bimodal distribution in exoplanet radii. We argue that in order to reproduce the distribution by Fulton et al. (2017) it is mandatory for there to be a paucity of exoplanets with masses above \$\textbackslash backslashrm \textbackslash backslashsim 8M\_\{\textbackslash backslashoplus\}\$. Furthermore, our best-fit result predicts an initial flat distribution in exoplanet occurrence for \$\textbackslash backslashrm M\_\{P\} \textbackslash backslashlesssim 8M\_\{\textbackslash backslashoplus\}\$ with a strong deficiency for planets with \$\textbackslash backslashrm \textbackslash backslashlesssim 3M\_\{\textbackslash backslashoplus\}\$. Our results are consistent with the \$\textbackslash backslashrm \textbackslash backslashsim 1.3R\_\{\textbackslash backslashoplus\}\$ radius peak mostly encompassing denuded exoplanets whilst the \$\textbackslash backslashrm \textbackslash backslashsim 2.4R\_\{\textbackslash backslashoplus\}\$ radius peak mainly comprising exoplanets with large hydrogen envelops},
