  abstract = {In order to exhume the buried signatures of ``missing planetary caustics'' in the KMTNet data, we conducted a systematic anomaly search to the residuals from point-source point-lens fits, based on a modified version of the KMTNet EventFinder algorithm. This search reveals the lowest mass-ratio planetary caustic to date in the microlensing event OGLE-2019-BLG-1053, for which the planetary signal had not been noticed before. The planetary system has a planet-host mass ratio of \$q = (1.25 \textbackslash backslashpm 0.13) \textbackslash backslashtimes 10\^\{-5\}\$. A Bayesian analysis yields estimates of the mass of the host star, \$M\_\{\textbackslash backslashrm host\} = 0.61\_\{-0.24\}\^\{+0.29\}{$\sim$}M\_\textbackslash backslashodot\$, the mass of its planet, \$M\_\{\textbackslash backslashrm planet\} = 2.48\_\{-0.98\}\^\{+1.19\}{$\sim$}M\_\{\textbackslash backslashoplus\}\$, the projected planet-host separation, \$a\_\textbackslash backslashperp = 3.4\_\{-0.5\}\^\{+0.5\}\$ au, and the lens distance of \$D\_\{\textbackslash backslashrm L\} = 6.8\_\{-0.9\}\^\{+0.6\}\$ kpc. The discovery of this very low mass-ratio planet illustrates the utility of our method and opens a new window for a large and homogeneous sample to study the microlensing planet-host mass-ratio function down to \$q \textbackslash backslashsim 10\^\{-5\}\$.},
